<subSubSection id="54ECB628417F7B4A4DD431DAC5DE4634" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="24E70895F5FADD36B3C3A8955307AFB9" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73EDC80965B774F53897DFBCF04B5F17" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">Male eyes contiguous dorsally; male occiput concave with a single row of postocular macrosetae present dorsally in male; antennal scape with macrosetae along medial surface; scape narrow and only slightly elongate; two pair of scutellar macrosetae; parafacial without setal pile; velutum patches absent on femora and sparsely present ventrally on gonocoxites; single anteroventral seta present apically on hind femur; wing cell m3 open; male genitalia with inner gonocoxal process well developed; gonostylus narrow apically; gonocoxites with medial atrium lacking; aedeagus with distiphallus broad apically; ventral apodeme of parameral sheath as broad plate, not forked; epandrium quadrangular. Female tergite 8 with narrow process anteromedially; two spermathecae, ducts joining to spermathecal sac duct; spermathecal sac present (Fig. 28A), female abdominal segment 8 with elongate posteriorly directed setae (Fig. 27).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="92423DC7B18F50605401B0288CD51B00" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" type="included species">
<paragraph id="0C924B0BA9255CC3A7A79B116023D7E7" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">Included species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D605A7F5A37D42A94D528853D5CD6755" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicName id="6AC2EB6FF23F16F745F9EA3F447CE0F9" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix warrumbungles" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="warrumbungles">Zelothrix warrumbungles</taxonomicName>
sp. n. and 
<taxonomicName id="B01D37303AEEF259D07E6E486C8F08DF" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix yeatesi" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yeatesi">Zelothrix yeatesi</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="37FD3F7DCBFFCC626EA3F93FF64C72C9" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="115" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" type="comments">
<paragraph id="8D902E4E0D755A45B4D509A9D6A3215F" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="468EBD6A63A3FD186576161FA80866E0" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="115" pageId="17" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicName id="E76973EEDC73C53949C92F3FFA007DC1" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. is a distinctive genus with a disparate distribution. Similar genera include 
<taxonomicName id="8C0231FF795FCB9D832F079E8712BED3" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="B02CF759CC3A6DE2CFAF9F9A7B240068" originalValue="Kröber">Kroeber</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6FD5AE5871FA9B46A0E734AFE30709FA" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Taenogerella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Taenogerella" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Taenogerella</taxonomicName>
Winterton &amp; Irwin and 
<taxonomicName id="B89839E41A60C503C9F0C1839CD1C273" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sidarena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sidarena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sidarena</taxonomicName>
gen. n. This new genus can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName id="621FA5525E0C0A70AB85BB459C667F64" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FC3CF6C739D47CC751442B2B1B0472EE" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sidarena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sidarena" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Sidarena</taxonomicName>
gen. n. by the presence of two scutellar macrosetae and a medial atrium in the male gonocoxites. The wing is extensively patterned in 
<taxonomicName id="01A6E0945EF06CB6B64CF166E470C241" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. but not banded as in 
<taxonomicName id="47D678E07EFAAB2B8F62011A613C4EAB" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Squamopygia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squamopygia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Squamopygia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="07EEB263C0F19B2ACE117D48EA066FAD" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. is separable from 
<taxonomicName id="00951612DF39949F5CCC36C9E3BA1E0B" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Taenogerella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Taenogerella" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Taenogerella</taxonomicName>
by the latter having a downward directed distiphallus in the male genitalia and three spermathecae (two 
<pageBreakToken id="30DD3DD26EA1182E94120B3824D70FDD" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" start="start">in</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName id="7E02097D4EC3250BDF078676E0B47BD6" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n.). A significant departure from the female genitalic complement of three spermathecae typically found in 
<taxonomicName id="225D1DBC04BADCB5002FB4DA66B3964B" lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Agapophytinae">Agapophytinae</taxonomicName>
, is that 
<taxonomicName id="925ADD1F6ACE07B5481240EABBE63827" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Zelothrix</taxonomicName>
gen. n. only has two spermathecae, a condition found in 
<taxonomicName id="CA21D8802C5929BC14AF94169A9E05AB" lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Therevinae">Therevinae</taxonomicName>
. No other genus of 
<taxonomicName id="9CA0D62AD2063AC7DA87F83645C42D21" lsidName="" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Agapophytinae">Agapophytinae</taxonomicName>
has two spermathecae, although the distantly related agapophytine genus 
<taxonomicName id="A7E8E20E5A56486C8345BBF7EFA02069" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Bonjeania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bonjeania" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bonjeania</taxonomicName>
Winterton &amp; Skevington has only a single spermatheca (
<bibRefCitation id="22935EF23B1B2831C5577853A9957F90" author="Winterton, SL" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="24" pageNumber="121" pagination="295 - 324" title="Phylogenetic revision of Bonjeania Irwin &amp; Lyneborg (Diptera: Therevidae)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.2000.00107.x" volume="25" year="2000">Winterton et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A1823425D87D4A8CF3AF71F27F43A252" pageId="18" pageNumber="115">
<taxonomicName id="022498A24C03BADCF499F6FE5CE8B45F" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix warrumbungles" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="warrumbungles">Zelothrix warrumbungles</taxonomicName>
sp. n. is a locally highly abundant species found mainly in Warrumbungle National Park (New South Wales) (Fig. 4), while 
<taxonomicName id="68205D3401FF561276D0F369B4348BEF" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2016" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Zelothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelothrix yeatesi" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yeatesi">Zelothrix yeatesi</taxonomicName>
sp. n. is a rarely collected species endemic to Porongurup National Park (Western Australia). The two species are very similar in appearance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A6FD6A12808B7671EA73405175C5678E" pageId="18" pageNumber="115" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B25E39D37E27F5479A5EA9835F37AACA" pageId="18" pageNumber="115">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="52D4F66C6B4F69A05F593198033DD47D" pageId="18" pageNumber="115">
This name is derived from the Greek, 
<normalizedToken id="B88CF09CDE3BB2E521C30C2B0F8A64E5" originalValue="Zelos–">Zelos-</normalizedToken>
emulation, and 
<normalizedToken id="090823379710B3E7C992C229D14263C2" originalValue="thrix–">thrix-</normalizedToken>
hair, for the setal pile on the female abdomen. Gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
